## 3. Solid Cache (Caching)

Solid Cache uses disk storage (SSD/NVMe) instead of RAM for caching.

### Key Benefits

- **No Redis dependency** - Uses database storage
- **Larger caches** - SSDs are cheaper than RAM
- **Longer-lasting caches** - Persist across restarts
- **Fast enough** - Modern SSDs are very fast
- **Cost-effective** - Significant savings on infrastructure

### Configuration

```ruby
# config/environments/production.rb

Rails.application.configure do
  # Solid Cache is default in Rails 8
  config.cache_store = :solid_cache_store
end
```

### Using Rails Cache

```ruby
# Basic caching
Rails.cache.fetch("articles/recent") do
  Article.published.recent.limit(10)
end

# Cache with expiration
Rails.cache.fetch("user/#{user.id}/dashboard", expires_in: 1.hour) do
  generate_user_dashboard(user)
end

# Write to cache
Rails.cache.write("key", "value", expires_in: 12.hours)

# Read from cache
value = Rails.cache.read("key")

# Delete from cache
Rails.cache.delete("key")

# Check existence
Rails.cache.exist?("key")
```

### Fragment Caching in Views

```erb
<!-- Basic fragment caching -->
<% cache @article do %>
  <%= render @article %>
<% end %>

<!-- Cache with expiration -->
<% cache @article, expires_in: 1.hour do %>
  <%= render @article %>
<% end %>

<!-- Russian Doll caching -->
<% cache ['articles', @articles.maximum(:updated_at)] do %>
  <%= render @articles %>
<% end %>
```
